{
  "text": "However, the actual increase in buoyancy due to thickening of the oceanic crust in the form of a seamount or oceanic plateau is generally quite small, and decreases rapidly with age of the plate [CITATION_1] . Other geologic processes such as serpentinization of oceanic mantle lithosphere can create a buoyancy anomaly exceeding that due to thickening of the crust in the form of seamounts, but the overall buoyancy increase remains small [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Geodynamic investigations of the effects of subduction of thick crust [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] indicate that a buoyant impactor is not a sufficient explanation for zones of flat subduction.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "129248284",
